With no recent news about communist guerrilla activities the likelihood of this resolving as yes is relatively small. The Duterte-inspired vigilante assault against drug dealers may kill many people randomly, not systematically.

Slight upward adjustment due to the conversation here: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/566081 Neither the offical rethoric nor the police practice changed as far as I know. For me, it was hard to get any data on casualties though, meaning I only found counts that predate the timeframe this questions asks about. As they far exceeded the number of fatalities that this questions asks about, I assume it is reasonable to assume that the amount of killed civilian in the philippine drug war will also stay above 1.000 in the timeframe this question asks about. However, I am not sure whether the number for Dutertes second year will reach 7.000 again. Probably not? If it is around 1.500-2.000, this might be ta reason to not judge it as a mass killing again, as data is hard to come by and it's hard to distinguish between combatants/gang members and civilians. -> 70% for now. I'll adjust my forecast towards the middle before this questions closes if I can't find new data.

Hello @mzapata, as you resolved this question positively in the last round, counting the deaths of the anti-drug operation as deliberate killings, i was just wondering if you got any information on how this might get handled in the future. My forecast is well above average for that reason and still it's only at 60% as I am unsure whether the people resolving these questions for you will apply the same reasoning this time (in my view, this is kind of a hard to judge grey area and I was taken by surprise in the last question relating to the philippines). Would be happy to hear your thoughts on this although I am sure it's hard to make any definitive statements. 
By the way: I think it's great that you started to set some impulses / provide some overview here on some of the questions! Best,

Based on general news and GJP consensus.

Hmm... according to the EarlyWarning website, the 17000 killings in Mexico, also mostly drug-related, were targeting mostly armed groups not civilians, so it wouldn't count, as killing of civilians were not systematic. I can see a similar situation profiling for the Philippines, even if the boundary is morally grey and difficult to define.

http://www.reuters.com/article/us-philippines-drugs-idUSKCN1B80D5
I am still pretty uneasy about my low number on this one.  If the police departments in, say, Manila, Angeles, Davao, Tacloban, and Zamboanga each murder 200, that's a thousand dead people at the instigation of the president, but it's not one armed group and it's all over the country.  The government clearly has embarked on a sustained campaign to let a lot of civilians get killed, but not in ways that clearly meet the various criteria for this question.  If my low number wins the guessing game about how this will be scored, I will be somewhere between uneasy and sick.

None of the anti-government groups can make this number unassisted, but the uniformed services of the Philippines government already have.  For our purposes, all will depend on how the scorers decide to count those murder victims.  For their families' purposes, counting them as "dead" is all the accuracy they need.

Cannot recall a year where ASG, MILF, NPA, or another group has tallied more than 1,000 fatalities.  A single incident in the dozens or hundreds range would provoke a strong response from the AFP, making a second massive attack less likely.  Sustained campaign inflicting 1,000 fatalities in the timeframe given very unlikely, but I could see it happening once in a 50 year period.

http://www.reuters.com/article/us-philippines-drugs-idUSKCN1AW0ZL?il=0
I think we are up against the vagaries of EWP's definitions and scoring algorithms on this one.  There is little doubt that armed and uniformed police and military will kill more than 1,000 civilians in this time frame.  However, the Cotabato City police won't make this number, nor will the Army nor whatever the old Philippine Constabulary are parading as now.  However, people with uniforms and weapons acting under the instructions or with the okey-dokey from the Prez will make this number and more easily, if they haven't done already.  Since it will involve several different armed groups in several different parts of the country over an extended period, one supposes these murders will all be put down to an unhappy and coincidental series of unfortunate events rather than a "campaign."   This will doubtless cheer up the surviving family members, if any, of the vics--who by the way will be precisely as dead as they would be if they had conformed to the official EWP definition.  Staying at 1, but none too happy about it, as you may have surmised.

assuming that the most likely (>50% chance) armed group is an armed terrorist group the stats on a terrorist group systematically killing more than a 1000 people are low. Worldwide in 2015, there was 1174 attacks and only 14 of those resulted in >100 deaths at a time. based n that data that gives a 0.14% chance of an attack happening that kills >100 people at a time.  in the phillipines in this same period specifically, the average death toll of an attack from a terrorist group is 0.54 deaths/attack. This would give a base rate chance of killing >1000 people in one attack (granted not the question but nonetheless instructive) of 0.00054%.  lastly, kidnapping involved 119 people taken hostage in 2015. Worldwide average of those returned unharmed was 33%. the rest were either killed, remain captive or are unreported. SO accounting for that base rate, the chance of getting killed from a kidnapping is 66%, meaning in 2015 roughly 79 people were killed from kidnaping alone. 7.6% of the target of 1000 deaths. Less than 1% of kidnappings worldwide resulted in >100 people kidnapping. this would only take us 6.6% of the way to 1000 deaths by kidnapping using the worldwide average of chance of death by kidnapping as our base rate. As such i think the chance of killing, systematically, more than 1000 people would be no higher than 5%, possibly lower.   i'm sorry this is very wordy, i;'ve attached the link to the data i've found about all this. https://www.state.gov/j/ct/rls/crt/2015/257526.htm feedback is welcome, especially if i'm interpreting the question wrong.

Without clarification if the drug war (and the subsequent targeting of "drug dealers") meets the definition above, it's unlikely this will be resolved as a yes. Additionally, the lack of clarity by the government and police forces makes it difficult to assess whether its a campaign by an armed group against civilians.

there is evidence that the police have killed more than this number in the first 9-12 months of the new president's 'war on drugs' https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/02/philippines-president-duterte-drugs-war-death-squads https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/01/24/deadly-milestone-philippines-abusive-drug-war assuming that police killings are included in the question above then there is a real possibility that this could occur over the next 12 months, assuming he trend continues

The Marawi conflict has resulted in 39 civilian casualties to date. What might move this questions towards Yes is if the government's implementation of martial law and its inability to provide to the internally displaced civilians results in widespread death as detailed in the question. While civilian casualties are expected to rise due to the conflict, it's unclear if the effects on displaced population are part of that calculus.
Low due to the historic peacefulness. Though potentially a drug war based riot could lead to an incident.

Given the definitions and criteria above, this (in my opinion) is really either 1% or 100%. The police have killed over 2,000 civilians in the campaign against drug traffickers. Whether that is an armed group engaging in a campaign policy that knowingly results in widespread civilian deaths is something the administrators will have to clarify. Considering that the question is being asked, I assume that the answer is no given that it is not a specific civilian group being targeted, but rather an ambiguous "drug dealer" group defined by the civilian population and the police. Therefore, I assess this as 1%, as there is no major campaign happening between armed forces that would reach this level. The Mindanao conflict, despite martial law being declared, has had relatively low casualty numbers, even with civilian displacement. There also doesn't appear to be an intentional policy to eliminate civilians.
The government and those it influences reaches that number with some regularity

In one year the philippines has had around 12,000 dead, thats roughly 1000 per month of. Add the impunity that comes with the downgrade of cases filed against the police officers who were charged for extrajudicial killings and the trend isn't going away soon
